x4freetext: Data only for U-233 (tbl.2).
Data only for U-233 (Tbl.5.2)
and full description of Double-energy double-velocity
measurement system for fission fragments
Y.Nakagome, I.Kimura, experimental site
I.Kanno.
Kyoto University reactor, KUR.
Thermal neutrons from a super mirror neutron
guide tube facility. The neutrons were guided through
the facility to a distance of 11.7 m from the reactor
core, and then collimated to 1cm * 7 cm by a beam slit
made of LiF. The neutron flux was 5.0E+07 n/cm2/sec.
.Thermal neutron spectrum.
The fission fragment velocities were detected by
time-of-flight in two opposite directions with flight
paths of 59 cm, while the fragment energies were
determined with Si detectors.  ( Double-energy double-
velocity measurement system for fission fragments was
used.) The resolution of TOF measurement system (about
Two 20 microgram/cm2 NE-102A plastic scin-
tillator film detectors, coupled via Lucite light
guides to photomultiplier tubes, were used as start
detectors for the time-of-flight. The scintillators
were placed at a distance of 3 cm from the uranium
target.
On each end of the flight tubes, three silicon
surface barrier detectors (SSB) were mounted to detect
the stop time and also to measure the fragment kinetic
energy. Energy calibration was performed by using a
spontaneous fission fragments of 252 Cf. The energy
resolution of the SSB (about 78 keV)
.The uranium targets were made from very thin nitro-
cellulose films in which organic uranium compounds
were dissolved. The diameter of the targets were 8 mm
and the thicknesses were 7 and 9 microgram/cm2 for
U-233 and U-235, respectively. The enrichments were
99.47 and 90% for the two isotopes, respectively.
